  "prompt": "What is Tacometer?",
  "response": "A tachometer is an instrument used to measure the rotational speed of a shaft or disk, typically expressed in revolutions per minute (RPM). Here are some key points about tachometers:\n\n1. Purpose\n- Measure rotation speed of engines, motors, and other rotating machinery\n- Provide real-time information about performance and efficiency\n\n2. Types\n- Mechanical tachometers\n- Electronic/digital tachometers\n- Optical tachometers\n- Contact and non-contact tachometers\n\n3. Applications\n- Automotive industry (monitoring engine speed)\n- Industrial machinery\n- Aviation\n- Manufacturing\n- Power generation\n- Automotive repair and maintenance\n\n4. Working Principles\n- Mechanical: Uses centrifugal force and spring tension\n- Electronic: Uses magnetic or optical sensors\n- Optical: Measures rotation using light and reflection\n\n5. Features\n- Displays RPM\n- Can include additional data like time and speed variations\n- Some models have data logging capabilities\n\nTachometers help monitor and optimize the performance of rotating equipment by providing accurate speed measurements.",
